Learning objectives

Functions of the kidneys

  • The kidneys do more than excrete nitrogenous waste
    • Filter the blood (wastes, hormone, drugs and free radicals)
    • Regulate blood volume, pressure andosmolarity(by regulating water output)
    • Regulate electrolyte and acid-base balance
    • Secrete the hormone erythropoietin (production of red blood cells)
    • Regulate calcium homeostasis (and bone metabolism) through synthesis of calcitriol
    • Can even synthesize glucose
  • Nitrogenous wastes are metabolic wastes containing small nitrogen compounds (-NH2)
    • Produced by proteins being hydrolysed to amino acids
    • From ammonia, which is converted to urea by the liver

Renal circulation

Figure 23.5

Renal circulation

Figure 23.6

  • Nephron is a functional unit of the kidney
    • Each afferent arteriole supplies one nephron
  • Glomerulus is a ball of capillary beds
    • Enclosed by glomerular capsule
      • Collectively called renal corpuscle
  • Efferent arterioles lead to a plexus of peritubularcapillaries surround the renal tube
    • The renal tube absorbs the water and solutes
  • Peritubular capillaries give rise to the cortical radialveins
  • Renal medulla receives only 1-2% of total renal flow
    • Capillaries of vasa recta carry away water andsolutes reabsorbed from the nephron loop

Renal circulation:The renal tubule

  • Proximal convoluted tubule focuses on absorption, sohas simple cuboidal epithelium with prominent microvilli
  • Nephron loop

  • Collecting duct (line with simple cuboidal epithelium)receive fluids from several tubules, and several combineto make a papillary duct, which flows to the minor calyx,then major calyx,etc

Urine Formation

Figure 23.9

  • Urine formation occurs in 3/4 stages:
    • Glomerular filtration
    • Tubular reabsorption and secretion
    • Water conservation

Glomerular filtration

Figure 23.8

  • Glomerular involves the movement of water and solutesfrom capillaries into the capsular space of the nephron
  • Utilises three barriers
    • Fenestrated endothelium of the capillary has poresthat are highly permeable but small enough to excludeblood cells
    • The basement membrane consists of a proteoglycangel that prevents large molecules and negativelycharged molecules
    • Filtration slits created by foot process of theglomerular capsule that also prevents large moleculesand negatively charged molecules
  • There is a net filtration pressure created by the largeinflow and small outflow of blood

Regulation of glomerular filtration

  • Glomerular filtration need to be regulated to avoid:
    • Dehydration and electrolyte depletion (too high)
    • Reabsorption of wastes (too low)
  • Four main mechanisms of regulation:
    • Myogenic mechanisms: smooth muscle contracts when stretched
    • Tubuloglomerularfeedback involves the juxtaglomerular apparatus (located at the end of the nephronloop) causing constriction of afferent arteriole to reduce blood flow in response to high blood flow
    • Sympathetic nerve fibres innervate and constrict afferent arterioles (as does adrenaline)
    • The renin-angiotensin-aldosterone mechanism: causes activation of angiotensin II (a hormone)
      • Constricts efferent arterioles (more than afferent arterioles)
        • Increases glomerular blood pressure (increases filtration)
        • Decreases blood pressure in peritubular capillaries (hereby encouraging reabsorption ofwater and solutes)
      • Stimulates adrenal cortex to secrete aldosterone, which stimulates water and solute reabsorptionin the distal and proximal convoluted tubules
      • Stimulates antidiuretic hormone (reabsorption in the collecting duct)
      • Stimulates a sense of thirst

Tubular absorption and secretion

  • Absorption and secretion essentially occur simultaneously in the:
    • Proximal convolutional tubule
    • The nephron loop
    • Distal convolutional tubule

The proximal convoluted tubule

Figure 23.16

  • There are two routes for reabsorption
    • Transcellular route
      • Substances pass through the cytoplasmand base of epithelial cells
    • Paracellular route
      • Substances pass through the tightjunctions between epithelial cells
    • Sodium reabsorption is the key because itcreates osmotic and electrical gradients thedrive water and other solutes
    • About 40-60% of urea is reabsorbed, butsince 99% of water is reabsorbed, there is ahigh concentration of urea in the filtrate
    • Peritubular capillary uptake water andsolutes via osmosis and solvent drag

The nephron loop

  • The primary function of the nephron loop is to generate an osmotic gradient
    • Reabsorbing 25% of Na+, K+and Cl-and 15% of the water
    • Cells in the thick segment of the ascending limb
      • Have proteins that bind Na+, K+and Cl-for cotransport into the cytoplasm
      • Na+, K+and Cl-leave the basolateral surface by active transport, but K+re-enters via Na+-K+pump
      • Are impermeable to water

The distal convoluted tubule and collecting duct

  • Fluid arriving at the distal convoluted tubule still contains about 20% of water 7% of the solutes from theoriginal glomerular filtrate
  • There are two kinds of cells:
    • Principal cells that have receptors for hormones and focus on salt and water balance
    • Intercalated cells that focus on acid-base balance
  • Major hormones
    • Aldosterone stimulates the reabsorption of Na+
    • Natriuretic peptides inhibitNaClreabsorption by the collecting duct (also increase filtration rate)
    • Antidiuretic hormone stimulates reabsorption of water
    • Parathyroid hormone stimulates calcium reabsorption in the distal convoluted tubule (also inhibitsphosphate reabsorption in the proximal convoluted tubule)

Water conservation

Figure 23.19

  • The collecting duct is able to produce hypertonic urine
    • Theosmolarityof the extracellular fluid is four times ashigh in the lower medulla as it is in the cortex
    • The medullary portion of the collecting duct is morepermeable to water than solutes

Water conservation

Figure 23.20

  • Theosmolarityof the extracellular fluid is four timesas high in the lower medulla as it is in the cortex
    • Due to a positive feedback loop
    • The nephron loop acts as counter-currentmultiplier
    • Also, urea is continually cycles from the collectingduct to nephron loop and back

Water conservation

Figure 23.20

Water conservation

  • The collecting duct can adjust water reabsorption to produce hypotonic or hypertonic urine, dependingon the body’s needs
  • In a state of hydration
    • Antidiuretic hormone is not secreted
    • The cortical part of the collecting duct reabsorbs salt without reabsorbing water
  • In a state of dehydration
    • Antidiuretic hormone is secreted
    • The medullary part of the collecting duct reabsorbs water, making the urine more concentrated

Summary of major solutes

Figure 23.22

  • Hormone affecting renal function

      • Targets nephron loop, DCT and PCT
    • Angiotensin II
      • Targets afferent and efferent arterioles and PCT
    • Antidiuretic hormone
      • Targets collecting duct
    • Noradrenaline and adrenaline
      • Targets juxtaglomerular apparatus and afferent arteriole
    • And many more…
